<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Dire Charm</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> would be even easier to use.  Currently, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Enchanters</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> cannot cast <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Summon Companion</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> on any charmed mob, including <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Dire Charm</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  So at the present, they could not acquire a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Dire Charmed</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> mob near the zone entrance, and bring it deeper into the dungeon without the aggro it would generate.  If they were <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> indifferent</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, they would be <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> invisible</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to all NPC's, and could be moved with little or no risk involved.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Response</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->: Only <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Summoned</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> pets are indifferent.  This would make <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Dire Charmed</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> pets relatively less powerful, and might address <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magician</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> concerns about <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Dire Charm</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> &quot;Around the Corner&quot; Pulls</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  This is not yet clarified in my mind, but imagine the following scenario.  There is a corner, or other obstacle, such as spawn of social KOS mobs, between you and and the mob you want to get to.  Because of the obstacle, you could not ordinarily pull or attack the distant mob without endangering yourself.  However, you can send an <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Indifferent Gobaner</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> past the obstacle to get at the more distant mob, thus <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;bypassing content&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  I can think of no specific example where this would help, but I am only one <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Mage</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Response</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->: This is only applicable in a small number of circumstances, and may not be significant in practice.  Only works at short distances.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Ignoring the obvious and frequently futile use of /pet back off there is no way if the pet was indifferent that the direwolf would aggro the pet and leave the mage.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->While I manage well enough with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> /pet back off, pet attack</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, especially as I tend to equip my pets with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Gnoll Hide Lariats</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, it seems a relatively small price to pay.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Not to imply that FoH would exploit anything on purpose but certainly they seem to be a crafty bunch of stratigists.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Knowing nothing about FoH, and not disparaging anyone, I deem it likely that a powerful guild would often tend to keep new tactics to themselves, and not reveal them to the community or <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Verant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> To prevent AFK exp I would suggest something along the lines of if a pet does not recieve a command from his master within the space of 1 hour the pet should poof.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Trivially bypassed with hot keys, please see my other thread on AFK experience.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Having pets share our factions is part of a pets challenge.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->As other posters have pointed out, this <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;challenge&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in practice eliminates pet from a broad range of circumstances.<br>
<br>
Even assuming that a &quot;skilled&quot; <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magician</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, under almost all circumstances no matter how dire, can control their pet, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;Risk Versus Reward&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> dictates that under many circumstances, pets be barred.  That is, the additional damage brought by the pet is far outweighed by the possible worst case scenario, i.e. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Gobaner</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> wanders off and brings back raid wiping train.  No rational raid leader would allow pets under that circumstance.<br>
<br>
Much remains to be done if we wish to pursue this.  I am certain that there are numerous consequences to this proposal that we have not yet divined.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Razamatazz Pizzazz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
